    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Preparation of Acid Halides</title>
    <para id="para-00001">Acid chlorides are prepared from carboxylic acids by reaction with thionyl chloride (SOCl<sub>2</sub>), as we saw in the previous section. Similar reaction of a carboxylic acid with phosphorus tribromide (PBr<sub>3</sub>) yields the acid bromide.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions of a carboxylic acid in which the OH group is green and oxygen is pink. The first reaction is catalyzed by SOCl2 (highlighted in blue) and the product is an acid chloride (RCOCl). The second reaction is catalyzed by PBr3 (highlighted in blue) and ether and the product is an acid bromide (RCOBr). The chlorine and bromine atoms are highlighted in blue. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Reactions of Acid Halides</title>
    <para id="para-00002">Acid halides are among the most reactive of carboxylic acid derivatives and can be converted into many other kinds of compounds by nucleophilic acyl substitution mechanisms. The halogen can be replaced by –OH to yield an acid, by –OCOR to yield an anhydride, by –OR to yield an ester, by –NH<sub>2</sub> to yield an amide, or by R′ to yield a ketone. In addition, the reduction of an acid halide yields a primary alcohol, and reaction with a Grignard reagent yields a tertiary alcohol. Although the reactions we’ll be discussing in this section are illustrated only for acid chlorides, similar processes take place with other acid halides.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows five reactions of an acid chloride. The structure of acid chloride is highlighted and shows a carbonyl group bonded to R and green chlorine. Hydrolysis yields RCOOH. Reaction with R’COO minus (highlighted in blue) yields an acid anhydride (RCO-blue O-COR’). Reaction with R’OH (highlighted in blue) yields an ester (RCO-blue OR’). Reaction with blue NH3 minus yields an amide (RCO bonded to blue amino group). Reaction with blue R’ 2CuLi yields a ketone (RCO-blue R’).The carbonyl oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Conversion of Acid Halides into Carboxylic Acids: Hydrolysis</title>
    <para id="para-00003">Acid chlorides react with water to yield carboxylic acids. This hydrolysis reaction is a typical nucleophilic acyl substitution process and is initiated by attack of water on the acid chloride carbonyl group. The tetrahedral intermediate undergoes elimination of Cl<sup>–</sup> and loss of H<sup>+</sup> to give the product carboxylic acid plus HCl.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which an acid chloride reacts with water (highlighted in blue) to yield two intermediates; the second intermediate reacts with base (highlighted in blue) to yield a carboxylic acid. The acid chloride shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a green chlorine. The oxygen of water shows four electrons. An arrow from these electrons points to the carbonyl carbon. An arrow from the carbonyl bond points to the oxygen that shows four electrons. The first intermediate shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to green chlorine and single bonded to a pink oxygen anion and blue oxygen cation. The pink oxygen shows six electrons. The blue oxygen shows two electrons and is bonded to two hydrogens. An arrow from the electrons of pink oxygen points to the C-pink O bond. An arrow from the C-Cl bond points to Cl. The second intermediate shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a blue oxygen cation that shows two electrons and is bonded to two hydrogens. The carbonyl oxygen shows four electrons. The base shows two electrons. An arrow from these electrons points to a blue hydrogen. An arrow from the bond between this hydrogen and oxygen cation points to the oxygen cation. The carboxylic acid shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to blue hydroxyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">Because HCl is formed during hydrolysis, the reaction is often carried out in the presence of a base such as pyridine or NaOH to remove the HCl and prevent it from causing side reactions.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Conversion of Acid Halides into Anhydrides</title>
    <para id="para-00005">Nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction of an acid chloride with a carboxylate anion gives an acid anhydride. Both symmetrical and unsymmetrical acid anhydrides can be prepared.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Sodium formate (highlighted in blue) reacts with Acetyl chloride in the presence of ether at 25 degree C to yield Acetic formic anhydride (64%). Sodium formate shows a hydrogen bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to an oxygen anion and then a sodium cation. Acetyl chloride shows a green chlorine bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. The carbonyl oxygen is highlighted in pink. Acetic formic anhydride shows a blue hydrogen bonded to a blue carbonyl group bonded to a blue oxygen that is bonded to another carbonyl group bonded to methyl group. The carbonyl oxygen is highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00005">
    <title>Conversion of Acid Halides into Esters: Alcoholysis</title>
    <para id="para-00006">Acid chlorides react with alcohols to yield esters in a process analogous to their reaction with water to yield acids. In fact, this reaction is probably the most common method for preparing esters in the laboratory. As with hydrolysis, alcoholysis reactions are usually carried out in the presence of pyridine or NaOH to react with the HCl formed.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Benzoyl chloride reacts with cyclohexanol in the presence of pyridine to yield Cyclohexyl benzoate (97%). Benzoyl chloride shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group bonded to green chlorine. Cyclohexanol shows cyclohexane bonded to blue hydroxyl group. Cyclohexyl benzoate shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group bonded to blue oxygen that is bonded to a cyclohexane. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_005.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00007">The reaction of an alcohol with an acid chloride is strongly affected by steric hindrance. Bulky groups on either partner slow down the reaction considerably, resulting in a reactivity order among alcohols of primary > secondary > tertiary. As a result, it’s often possible to selectively esterify an unhindered alcohol in the presence of a more hindered one. This can be important in complex syntheses in which it’s sometimes necessary to distinguish between similar functional groups. For example,</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00006">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which an alcohol reacts with an acid chloride in the presence of pyridine to yield a product. The alcohol shows a cyclohexane with C1 bonded to a hydroxy methyl group (blue OH) and C4 bonded to a pink hydroxyl group. The blue OH is labeled ‘Primary alcohol (less hindered and more reactive).’ The pink OH is labeled ‘Secondary alcohol (more hindered and less reactive).’ The acid chloride shows a methyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a green chlorine. The product shows a cyclohexane with C4 bonded to a pink hydroxyl group and C1 bonded to a methylene group that is bonded to a blue oxygen bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
     
