   <section id="sect-00007">
    <title>Conversion of Acid Halides into Amides: Aminolysis</title>
    <para id="para-00010">Acid chlorides react rapidly with ammonia and amines to give amides. As with the acid chloride-plus-alcohol method for preparing esters, this reaction of acid chlorides with amines is the most commonly used laboratory method for preparing amides. Both monosubstituted and disubstituted amines can be used, but not trisubstituted amines (R<sub>3</sub>N).</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions. In the first reaction 2-Methylpropanoyl chloride reacts with 2 moles of ammonia (highlighted in blue) to yield 2-Methylpropanamide (83%) and ammonium chloride (ammonium ion (highlighted in blue) bonded to green chloride ion). 2-Methylpropanoyl chloride shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group that is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom and carbonyl group on the right. The carbonyl group is bonded to a green chlorine. 2-Methylpropanamide is similar to 2-Methylpropanoyl chloride but the chlorine is replaced by blue amino group. In the second reaction Benzoyl chloride reacts with 2 moles of NH(CH3)2 (highlighted in blue) to yield N N-Dimethylbenzamide (92%) and another product. Benzoyl chloride shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group bonded to a green chlorine atom. N N-Dimethylbenzamide shows benzene bonded to carbonyl group bonded to a blue nitrogen that is bonded to two methyl groups. The other product shows two blue methyl groups bonded to a blue positively charged amino group bonded to green chloride ion. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00011">Because HCl is formed during the reaction, two equivalents of the amine must be used. One equivalent reacts with the acid chloride, and one equivalent reacts with the HCl by-product to form an ammonium chloride salt. If, however, the amine component is valuable, amide synthesis is often carried out using one equivalent of the amine plus one equivalent of an inexpensive base such as NaOH. For example, the sedative trimetozine is prepared commercially by reaction of 3,4,5-trimethoxybenzoyl chloride with the amine morpholine in the presence of one equivalent of NaOH.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00008">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which 3 4 5-Trimethoxybenzoyl chloride reacts with Morpholine (highlighted in blue) in the presence of sodium hydroxide and water to yield Trimetozine (an amide) and sodium chloride (chlorine is green). 3 4 5-Trimethoxybenzoyl chloride shows benzene with C1 bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to green chlorine. C3 C4 and C5 are bonded to a methoxide group each. Morpholine shows a cyclohexane with an oxygen and nitrogen monohydride. Trimetozine shows benzene with C1 bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to cyclohexane (highlighted in blue) with an oxygen and nitrogen. C3 C4 and C5 are bonded to a methoxide group each. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <example id="exam-00001">
    <title>Synthesizing an Amide from an Acid Chloride</title>
    <para id="para-00012">How might you prepare <emphasis effect="italics">N</emphasis>-methylpropanamide by reaction of an acid chloride with an amine?</para>
    <para id="para-00013"><title><span class="red-text">Strategy</span></title> As its name implies, <emphasis effect="italics">N</emphasis>-methylpropanamide can be made by reaction of <emphasis effect="italics">methylamine</emphasis> with the acid chloride of <emphasis effect="italics">propanoic</emphasis> acid.</para>
    <para id="para-00014"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Propanoyl chloride reacts with 2 moles of methylamine (highlighted in blue) to yield N-Methylpropanamide and another product. Propanoyl chloride shows an ethyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a green chlorine. Methylamine shows a methyl group bonded to amino group. N-Methylpropanamide shows an ethyl group bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to blue nitrogen monohydride that is bonded to blue methyl group. The other product shows a blue methyl group bonded to ammonium ion (highlighted in blue) that is bonded to green chloride ion. The carbonyl oxygens are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_04_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </example>
    </section>
    
